To Install ELK follow the below steps
•	Download all the below files
o	https://www.elastic.co/downloads/elasticsearch
o	https://www.elastic.co/downloads/beats/filebeat
o	https://www.elastic.co/downloads/logstash
o	https://www.elastic.co/downloads/kibana
•	If you’re in windows, then install it one by one.
•	In you’re into other platform like Linux then follow the below steps
o	Download all the file like above but choose Linux while downloading
o	Now open the terminal and run these command one by one
o	Sudo apt -get update
o	Sudo apt -get install -y openjdk-8-jdk
o	Sudo apt -get update
o	Sudo apt -get -y install nginx
o	Wget -q0 – http://artifacts.elastic.co/GPG-KEY-elasticsearch | sudo apt -key add –
o	Echo “deb https://artifacts.elastic.co/packages/7.x/apt stable main” | sudo tee -a /etc/apt/sources.list.d/elastic-7.x.list
o	Sudo apt update
o	Sudo apt install elasticsearch
o	Sudo apt install kibana
o	Sudo apt install logstash
o	sudo apt install filebeat
•	Now to activate the elasticsearch use the below command
o	Sudo nano /etc/elasticsearch/elasticsearch.yml
o	Now uncomment the below text from the file
o	Cluster.name: my-application
o	Node.name: node-1
o	Path.data: /var/lib/elasticsearch
o	Path.logs: /var/log/elasticsearch
o	Network.host: localhost #remove the ip address and type localhost
o	http.port: 9200
o	now press ctrl + o enter
o	now press ctrl + X
o	sudo systemctl start elasticsearch  #to start the service
o	sudo systemctl status elasticsearch #to check the service is enable or not
o	curl localhost:9200

•	Now to activate kibana use the below command
o	Sudo nano /etc/kibana/kibana.yml
o	Now uncomment the below text from the file
o	Server.pot: 5601
o	Server.host: “localhost”
o	Now press ctrl+ O enter
o	Now press ctrl + X
o	Systemctl status kibana
o	Sudo systemctl start kibana
o	sudo systemctl status kibana
•	Sudo apt install apache2-utils and click on Yes
•	Sudo htpasswd -c /etc/nginx/htpasswd.users kibana
•	Now enter the new password
Now we are moving the nginx configuration files to another folder
•	Sudo mv /etc/nginx/sites-available/default 	/etc/nginx/sites-available/new-default
Now we are adding the new configuration file into default nginx location
•	Sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/default
•	Type the below script
Server {
	Listen 80;
	Server_name	 3.131.91.105;	#type your ip address
	Auth_basic “Restricted Access”;
	Auth_basic_user_file /etc/nginx/htpasswd.users;
	Location / {
		Proxy_pass http://localhost:5601;
		Proxy_http_version 1.1;
		Proxy_set_header upgrade $http_upgrade;
		Proxy_set_header Connection ‘upgrade’;
		proxy_set_header Host $host;
		proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
		}
	}
•	Sudo systemctl restart nginx
•	Now go to browser and enter your password
•	It will load the elastic
•	Now go to home
•	Now click on try on sample data
Now we are testing the sample data in the elastic
•	Click add on sample web logs
•	Click to 3dot and select dashboard
•	Now that sample web logs traffic will show click on that
•	Now you can see different types of visualization and graphs

Now if you want to collect the real time data and want to visualize
•	Now from the filebeat we are going to collect the data
•	Sudo filebeat modules list 	#it will display all the filebeat commands
•	Sudo filebeat modules enable system
•	Sudo filebeat modules list # now you can see the system with enable option in the list
•	Sudo filebeat modules enable apache
•	Sudo filebeat modules list # now you can see the system with enable option in the list
•	Sudo nano /etc/filebeat/module.d/system.yml
•	Now in the module:system type
#Syslog
	Syslog:
	Enabled: true
	var.paths: [“/var/log/syslog*”]

	#Authorization logs
	Auth:
	enabled: true
	var.paths: [“/var/log/auth.log*”]
Now save the file. Press Ctrl + O and Ctrl +X
•	Sudo systemctl restart filebeat
•	Sudo systemctl status filebeat
•	Now click on 3dot
•	Now scroll down and go to management section
•	Now click on stack management
•	Now click on index management in data section
•	Now go to kibana and click on index patterns
•	Now type filebeat* (it will display all the related files)
•	Now select the file and click on next step
•	Now select @timestamp
•	Now click on create index pattern
